## Typical prompts

These are example user requests `/ship` handles well. The skill verifies the readiness gate, surfaces the branch-outcome decision, and writes the canonical release-gate artifact.

### Prompt 1 ŌĆö Standard merge

> "Ship it."

`/ship` walks Step 1 to verify all five Law 1 checks (tests fresh in this turn, CI green on head SHA, `pass_round` current, `/qa` verdict ready or ready_with_findings, branch up-to-date with base). If any check is stale or fails, Step 2 refuses the merge and surfaces which check blocked. If all pass, Step 3 surfaces the four-outcome decision; on Merge, Steps 4ŌĆō7 push the branch (if needed), record `release_gate: ready` in `release-gate-record.md`, and write `pull-request.json` with the merged status.

### Prompt 2 ŌĆö P0 surfaced but operator wants to merge anyway

> "QA found a P0 but I want to ship ŌĆö we'll patch it next sprint."

Per Law 2, "no silent merges past failed checks." Step 1's check 4 reads the `/qa` verdict (`not_ready` because of the P0); Step 2 refuses the merge and surfaces the failing check with its block reason. The exception path is the only release valve, and it requires explicit `AskUserQuestion` confirmation plus a recorded rationale in `release-gate-record.md` (per Law 2). `/ship` does not silently override; the operator chooses to invoke the exception path on the record, or routes back through `/qa`.

### Prompt 3 ŌĆö In-progress branch the team isn't ready to delete

> "This branch isn't ready to merge but we don't want to discard it ŌĆö we'll come back to it."

Step 3 surfaces the four-outcome `AskUserQuestion`; the operator picks Keep alive. `/ship` records `release_gate: deferred` with a one-paragraph reason ("blocked on dependency X", "awaiting design review", "scheduled for next window"). The branch remains; `/closeout` may not consume it yet. This is Law 3 outcome 2 ŌĆö an honest ending, not a failure.

These prompts test that `/ship` enforces the readiness gate (Law 1), refuses to ship broken (Law 2), and surfaces the four explicit branch outcomes (Law 3) rather than auto-picking or silently merging.

